Russian President Vladimir Putin signed the law on the introduction of administrative responsibility for violation of the term and procedure of payment of goods (work, services) in the execution of purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to address the very acute problem of non-performance of its obligations by customers in the conduct of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not get paid for already executed state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia gave the order to the Prosecutor General’s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unfair customers, who entered into contracts that were not backed by financing, anyway tried to avoid the obligations taken on payment and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in the interest of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the prosecutor’s office has submitted 9.7 thousand submissions, according to the results of their consideration of disciplinary responsibility attracted 4.5 thousand officials, to the administrative - 533, to the investigative bodies for the organization of the proceedings
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs was repaid in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles.
And these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
Substantial debts have resulted in numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts.
This is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for providing social transport services for several million rubles.
The man invested all his means of trading, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is an increasing financial burden on wages, taxes, loans that would lead to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek help from the prosecutor’s office.
In a number of regions, the problem has now been levelled as much as possible.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by the prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the prosecutor’s office operates under manual crisis management.
The Prosecutor-General personally conducts outreach meetings with representatives of the local authority, which deal with all the violations and measures taken by the Prosecutor-General to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers, which will be able to improve the implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ on amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences in connection with the establishment of administrative responsibility of officials of the customer for violation of time and order
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation, which provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by the official of the customer of the term and order of payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he is awaiting disqualification for a period of one year to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novels in practice.
The Civil Rights Protection Group has issued a warning on the movement to Missouri
The National Association for the Promotion of the Advancement of Colored Population has issued a warning for color people traveling to Missouri due to the state’s discriminatory policies and attacks on racist soil.
The statement of the group reads as follows: “Warning of non-travellers of the National Association for the Promotion of the Advancement of Colored Population, valid until August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, guests and citizens of the State of Missouri to be particularly attentive and to show compassion.
According to the National Association for the Promotion of the Advancement of Colored Population, to declare a warning on the movement of the group has triggered a law recently adopted in Missouri, which makes it harder for people to win lawsuits related to discrimination, as well as the fact that their law enforcement agencies are not shy.
“You have people who are in violation of human rights.
They are being stopped on the roads because of the color of the skin, beaten and killed,” said Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first such warning issued by the organization against the U.S. state.
The group referred to incidents such as the humiliation of black students on racial grounds at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he had run out of gasoline during a state trip, and the Missouri State Police arrested him without bringing charges of a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri State Attorney General’s Office that the likelihood of being stopped on the road for black drivers is 75 per cent higher than for white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is to keep people aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People have to be prepared one way or another, whether they’ll take the money to pledge or tell their relatives that they’re traveling around the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, there were 100 hate crimes registered in Missouri in 2015, making the state the 16th in the state by number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to the new law in the state of Missouri, after which it will be more difficult to initiate a lawsuit against a legal entity in connection with housing or labour discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws, according to which local law enforcement authorities were ordered to arrest people for violation of the ACLU, to commit immigration.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department in relation to other countries, but recent public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
