Now the Trump White House is aiming for the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when it begins to fight statues.
The Americans understand this no worse than all the others - hence the deliberate theatrical portrayal of Saddam Hussein's statue on Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump administration, no doubt knew what he was doing when he carried a symbolic torch over the Statue of Liberty during a fierce dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president’s proposals for a sharp reduction in legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't try on the statue itself.
Counts of the owners of walking ships and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would have lynched him if he tried to do so.
But he tried to make sense of it, and especially the meaning that was attributed to her in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when Emma Lazarus' poems were added to the pedestal.
As Miller said to Acosta: “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are talking about has been added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.
Miller put the facts right, but as he himself said, it's not really about history.
It is about the current sound of the striking words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds, who dream of breathing freely, / The unfortunate rejections of your abundant possessions."
Never before have "unfortunate discards" been so visible on our screens.
Miller didn’t do literature – he made it clear that in America, Trump doesn’t expect these people.
This dispute over the meaning of the statue is part of a wider political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute over the meaning of America.
Lazarus – and her friends, who were struggling to put her words on the statue posthumously – understood very well that they were committing a perfectly political act.
The sculpture by design was to mark the connection between the French and American republics by means of a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poetry the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of poetry and image was a brilliant feminist movement and a crushing attack on American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though to change it back.
In 2010, a voiceless Rash Limbo, a kind of John the Baptist who heralded Trump’s arrival, argued that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather she is an early neoconservative, carrying America’s flame to the dark world: “Freedom goes ahead.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States.”
Against the usual Limbo here really got to the point.
The meaning of the statue depends exclusively on the point of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she would have been seen by the improbable, unfortunate, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often difficult voyage.
This means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are looking for refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue responds to them with words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to illuminate the way, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their power.
