“No one decides to go to the village after five o’clock,” she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupiers.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands has quickly turned its anger against the government of Jakarta, which retains tight control over the region, without allowing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a half-hour flight from Jaipur, the administrative center of the province, to Nabira, and then a five-hour trek on the rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city with a population of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses lined with bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted with rust in various shades of pink.
Few of the Indonesians came here, not to mention the journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the pagodas worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear this garment,” Degei says, pointing to his bright, hand-studded turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to wear only leaves on the body.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy levels among the worst in Asia.
But it is also an Indonesian gold land.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran, a Phoenix-based company, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a high-altitude province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport acquired gold and copper for about $3.1 billion.
In addition, Papua can boast of forest reserves, the value of which is estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that the powerful Indonesian armed forces retain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by the New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and units, including up to $150,000 per officer.
The demands of greater autonomy on the part of the papayas threaten the existence of this golden dwelling and are mercilessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and deprived of liberty.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass killings of indigenous peoples in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” the report, published in 2016 by the Brisbane Diocese, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – especially frequent, as claimed in another report by the prosecution and torture.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because the incidents take place every week,” says Andreas Harsono, who is researching Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The gaiks were delayed, as Papuan resources attracted an influx of migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The 3.5 million population of the province is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese lavochees, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado", served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants began selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than native Papuans,” explains Abet You, a twenty-four-year-old native of Paniai, who moved to Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, due to work.
“Because of this, the natives of Papua – the mother-mother (women) of Papua – have lost their sales market.”
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, known to the people as Jokovi, vowed to deal with inequality and violations of rights in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, a former butcher has pledged support for 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” You said.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokova Paniai experienced a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing Christmas hymns at the skeleton in Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javette Thebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and witnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, pursued the children and beat them with examples of rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Aimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a government building near the electoral commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them the ritual hunting bows and performed the waita, the dance of the Papuan tribe mee pago: they ran round and depicted the bird singing.
Some protesters began to pour stones into the police station and military base.
When the situation worsened, soldiers on internal radio were given the order: “If the crowd shows resistance more than three times, shoot them”, – so he sounded, as stated in the official document, which was seen by the correspondents of the magazine “TIME”, but which was not found.
Fifty-year-old Jeremiah Kayame, head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, addressing the crowd with a request to break up their homes.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I came back, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the wing of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot him, but says the bullet flew off the side of a bunch of assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
A local resident of Alfius Jouva was hit three times, according to his cousin, who became a witness to the shooting.
“I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” said Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
“I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, the senior police inspector of Papua, told reporters that his officers were only “defending” their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Pujo Sulistio, a Papuan police official, said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed, and far more were injured.
The news of the killings reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Djokovic delivered a speech in Jaipur, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the issue of historical abuses by the authorities in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never repeats itself again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, the Minister of Security, Viranto, said he would set up a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights violations.
But almost immediately the answers were sent.
“Most of the violations took place a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early zeroes.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be done,” he said.
Viranto then gave up his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to set up an organization to consider complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided by the court.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during a bloodied vote for East Timor’s independence in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been committed, including the incident in Paani.
The families of the victims from Paniai met with similar statements with a dark mistrust.
“I’ve been asked four times in the last three years, but there hasn’t been any change at all,” says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid that the military will arrest me, I’m afraid I’ll be shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury the four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in the neighbouring Paniai district of Deiai.
During the clash between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to help take the unconscious man to the hospital, one person died and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Douw, drowned while catching fish in a runaway river, died on the way to the hospital.
The angry residents of the village protested in front of the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to police, residents of the village poured stones into officers, who in response made warning shots.
But locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retribution,” said twenty-year-old Dominga Badia, who lives near the hospital and saw how quickly the wounded were being delivered.
“I hid in my house for two days.”
The Deiai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called in for a response, and the mobile police brigade was withdrawn from the region.
The Panya has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development causes dissatisfaction among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the territory of the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by orchestrating sporadic attacks and raids by kidnapping Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested in Paniai in recent years and indiscriminately detained by the military on the pretext of “protecting national independence”.
Some of them never came back.
Among the population of Papua Paniai is considered a “careful, forgotten place”.
Poverty increases dissatisfaction.
A small portion of the rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
The bread is not available to the same degree.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly a note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can take care of four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten clubs of note cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, the economic inequality between indigenous Papuans and new migrants has increased, which has come in large numbers since the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
Few existing jobs are usually made available to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papayas rarely have enough money or skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village ... because there’s no work or money here,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basil Lonshan were deported from Papua for “insufficient coordination with the relevant organizations” despite being given rare permits to conduct the video.
According to Felim China, the deputy director of the organization Human Rights Watch, the promises made during the election campaign of Djokovic to lift restrictions on the work of the media in order to promote transparency and development were not fulfilled.
"Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebel eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua, are facing new dangers: visa waivers and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of attention from the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to the immediate neighbors of Papua.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – appealed to the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Papua shooting.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
The representative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Indonesia, Arramanat Nasir, refrained from the group’s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that “In Indonesia there is still a democratic system and there is a free press, so to hide the evidence of human rights violations would have been
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by the Dutch human rights ambassador Kyes Van Baar, visited Jaipur on May 4, the locals broke the silence, asking: "We want freedom", as a source who has also been present at the ceremony claims.
In Indonesia, a new presidential election will take place in 2019, but the Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Djokovic again.
“Jakowi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the shooting in Paniai,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokovi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from the greedy army, are in poverty, and their education and health are in poor condition.
Gobai says that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other papuas, consider their voice given to Jokovi, a debt that he must pay.
“They don’t need money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai carried out the last symbolic act of non-compliance: buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military site.
Knowing that justice is likely to never disappoint, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget about their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” says Jacobus, without raising his head.
“What else did we have to do?”
