Judges offer protection from presidents
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The SCHR proposes to limit the powers of the Presidents of the Courts and to introduce their elective powers.
For the courts of appeal and cassation of the Supreme Court of Justice wants to introduce special districts, which will not be tied to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The SCHR has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs at the order of Vladimir Putin of January 3, 2017, which the President gave after meeting with the members of the Council.
During the meeting with the members of the Council on 8 December 2016, individual cases of judicial arbitral proceedings were discussed, as well as problems of public control in the places of detention of citizens (see "I" of 9 December).
As a result of the work of the SCHR, 25 proposals were made, which dealt with both issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of other judges.
If the candidate for the post of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the President of the court, in the opinion of the SCHR, should present him for appointment without having the right to refuse as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to distribute cases for consideration between judges.
To do this, according to experts, can be a specially written computer program.
Also, the SCHR believes that the president is not entitled to “predict the results of the judge’s qualification certification, to initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and “assign them powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation.”
Now all the presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the presentation of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
To protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the SCHR proposes to reorganise appeals and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The SCHR says that “it is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation bodies not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
The experts take the practice of arbitral tribunals as the basis.
There are “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee, at the expense of this, greater independence from regional officials, which make the use of “telephone law” difficult.
The World Court of Human Rights (WCC) proposes to strengthen people’s councils to consider with their participation some “categories of civil and administrative matters”.
For example, about deprivation of parental rights, about restoration at work, about protection of honor and dignity, about deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"These are just our proposals," said the "I" member of the SCHR, a judge of the Constitutional Court in the resignation of Tamara Morshchakov.
She also recalled that the President’s mandate was not only to the LHR, but also to the Supreme Court (the Supreme Court), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the execution of the order by the police (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the human rights officer in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effective the independence of justice is being ensured in the Russian Federation, the President of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev should be until September 1.
