Tyumen Prosecutor's Office Fights HIV-Dissistant
The prosecutor’s office challenged the decision of the Kaliningrad court of Tyumen, which has suspended the criminal case against a local resident who has died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died due to the fact that the mother is HIV-deprived and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecution believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished, so as not to create a precedent for other HIV-dissidents.
The case against the resident of Tyumeni was brought under article 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (cause of death due to negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection at stage 4B.
According to the prosecutor’s office, the mother herself is HIV-infected.
“The woman was not treated by herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist,” the prosecutor’s office said.
The criminal case was brought to the Tyumen District Court of Kalinin, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that "forgive a wife who has no claim to her, she smoothed out the damage and made excuses".
The Prosecutor ' s Office did not agree with the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the termination order be revoked and that it be re-examined.
The girl died, and the harm caused by the crime is impossible.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her with a dangerous infection," the prosecutor's office said.
According to the supervisory authority, she should be punished, otherwise her example will be followed by other HIV-dissidents.
As reported in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care due to the refusal of their parents.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV, changed their opinion - allowed to make a diagnosis, started taking drugs," said Elena Loseva, the press secretary of the Center for AIDS.
According to her, it is impossible to affect parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children are able to be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV-dissidents?
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first study in Russia of the so-called HIV-dissidents movement.
HIV-dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS-service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and they see a serious threat in their spread.
