Italy is tightening its tone against the ships of NGOs that rescue migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs belonging to the rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turkish daily Press.
Minniti’s warning came the day after the Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet, on suspicion that his crew was actually cooperating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which only worked for a year, declined to comment on the substance of the detailed allegations made against it by Italian prosecutor Ambroseo Cartosio.
“For us, saving human life is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue to operate in the search and rescue zone right now,” the organization said in a statement.
“We will only be able to assess all the allegations made right now after we have collected all the information and will be able to assess the situation.”
Italian authorities have been monitoring the ship Juventa, owned by Jugend Rettet, since October.
His crew is suspected of having taken on board the migrants, who were sent directly to them by human traffickers, and allowed smugglers to leave along with the boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the indictment, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the area, rather than humanitarian fury, than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct mainly assumes that Juventus-type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to abide by the code: "Save the Children", Maltese MOAS and "Pro-Activa Expanded Volumes" from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considers the new rules unnecessary, but acceptable, provided they do not involve any "significant changes or disruptions" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is also the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said a sharp decline in the number of migrants arriving in Italy in recent weeks as a result of rescue operations indicated that efforts to support Libya’s coastguard and co-operation with local mayors were bearing fruit.
“In the last few days we have started to see the light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
