Startups That Will Help Your Company Not Become Another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among employees of her e-commerce startup, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, dishonest.
And even though she promised anonymity, some staff members did not trust the process.
“He has never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, managing director of a San Francisco-based company of 75 Madison Reeds, which deals with e-commerce in the field of hair care.
Therefore, she turned to third parties for help.
There is now a new kind of start-ups in the field of working with staff that help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software, the purpose of which is the measurement of employee involvement, they allow companies to make express inquiries, to contact certain teams and demographic groups, to offer employees anonymity and hotline for complaints, and in some cases, to allow complaints.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, but where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Redwood City startup, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure engagement.
Errett said she had gained a greater understanding of what her employees thought and felt over the three years of using “Glint.”
In addition to express surveys and surveys of certain teams, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in a visual form, which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows them to understand why.
Companies are little aware that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become the next Uber, which turned out to be involved in a scandal when a former employee posted a blog post in which he described an aggressive situation that did not go away.
For startups like Glint, it’s a desire to control the situation – an opportunity for profitable business.
According to the Internet portal “Let’s talk about payment” dedicated to financial technologies, the global management, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado-based startup, Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a decline in Uber’s reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Recently “Uber” appeared among customers.
Like “Glint”, “Convertent” allows companies to send custom-made opinion polls, collect confidential responses in real-time, and view heat maps of problem zones.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages, which allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if they touch the top manager, the complaints go straight to the direction.
“The public opinion court seized power from inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it is found that the company treats employees poorly or behaves unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees, has been using Convertent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company’s head office.
Earlier, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a phone number or an email from the head office, file an official complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and uncomfortable experience, said James Vitrano, chief legal officer of Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employees’ complaints.
Now that the company is using the “Convertent” service, the problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay — can be quickly detected and dealt with.
“I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employee situation,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday network’s risk management group.
“And we’re protecting our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Quinland, the companies began to take ethics, values and employee involvement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen suffered a breakdown due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron case.
But only when “social networks got mass distribution,” companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution on the network.
“Before we started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both “Glint” and “Convercent” offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has received approval from venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, “Convercent” received $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, which resulted in the company’s total capital reaching $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, resulting in the company’s total capital of $60 million.
These investments are unlikely to be surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than it was before.
In markets with fierce competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects – this is just the necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued, and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, they feel that they hear them, and that the work they do brings results, they are more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at Inverlin.
Investors earn income when business from their portfolio goes well; business from companies goes well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s not surprising that they find support.
As the culture experts at the workplace say, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company's custodians take action.
In fact, if the company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if the changes don’t come fast enough, or don’t come at all, disappointment can develop, and employees lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you need to be prepared to hold 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rat, president of consulting at Kotter International, a management firm that had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, employees will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
You don't mind?
If you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, the Madison Reed company, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day someone reports a problem with the help of Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees, dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday receives new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it to retain more effectively employees in the industry, known for its high personnel turnover.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose companies.
