Create a novel-comics: A Castle in English History
In the recent past, Scottney's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a port for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the Bayle River valley in Kent County he observed a turbulent history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a land-haired and historical record, to a novel-comic.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
"The Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Equarian era and tells of the families who lived in Scotland; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Brian May Smith, William Eckley, and William Eckley.
It’s not Rods’ first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote “The Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories” – a collection of documents from the British Library; this project unexpectedly shook him to the core.
“I could have just scratched my finger at the end of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent who worked on the Jacobites,” he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell smoke, because in those times for lighting were on fire.
And in 300 years, in the future, you seem to be there too.
"I love the archives!"
For a person who is so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Fund and the English Artistic Council and living in the castle for four months (“Honestly, I’m a little bit stuck there”) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle for days, walked through the archives, and looked at numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of the genie on the walls or bottles, centuries in ruins.
He was walking through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to the foresters, gardeners, and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Later that night, he drank whiskey and sat down to write.
The history of Scott's castle is not much studied because the National Fund gained full access to it only in 2006 when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassie, died.
When Rods arrived ten years later, the staff only began to deal with the archive, which he described as “what the aristocrats had thrown into the limelight for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think the land disputes are boring,” says Rods, “but there were two families fighting for this birch.
That's it, guys!"
In some of the stories of the castle collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider explorations in English history: for example, in the "Laboratory", the hero departs from the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is information about the rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called ‘The Knights of Kent and Sussex’,” Rhodes says.
“The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought the rebellion was a good start.
Maybe they were related?”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom Darrell's family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Contrabandist", about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funerals by pounding the tomb with stones (this was discovered a few years after the tomb was excavated).
Darrells is a favorite of the Rhodes family of all who settled in Scotty: “Gentlemen seem to have been the perfect villain, forever in debt and spent money on what they couldn’t afford.
In different generations, the Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women – I imagine them as a company of nice guys who can take care of the heirs of great estates.”
After finishing his job at the castle, Rods is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish Highlands, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamianmyaka - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it grew again in the forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he says.
“I felt like this: damn it, I have to go back to real life again.”
