Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease the pain.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies say the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help ease the symptoms of those who suffer from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and abdominal swelling, chronic or bleeding, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to relieve symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the gut are monitoring that harmful microbes that come with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of starting the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protect the body and at the same time do not harm sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too strongly broken in the direction of inflammation, this can lead to inflammatory diseases of the intestine.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the gut appear to have an increased cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri, - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in mice, the more these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan can contribute to a more tolerant and less prone environment in the gut.
A postdoc by Dr. Luisa Servantes-Barraganvas, studying the variety of immune cell-enhancing tolerances, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line, but contained them separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by mouse gut microbiomes — communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mouse gut cell DNA was sequenced and six types of bacteria were found to be present in mice that have immune cells but are absent in mice that do not have them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cell received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of fluid — without bacteria — to the underdeveloped immune cells isolated from the mice.
Immune cells have been converted into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of processing tryptophan, known as indol-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were reduced by twice, the number of cells also fell by twice.
Dr. Servantes-Barrag<0xC3><0xA1>n explains that people have the same increased cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as well as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found.
She says: “Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
“High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to an expansion of their population.”
