The property for the White House was paid to taxpayers in thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to force a helicopter of the Marines to the South Pole at an event dedicated to U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as “Marine One” when the president is on board, became the central element of the July 17 event at the White House, which showcased American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials have examined technology products from all 50 states, according to the report.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was on display next to a yacht from Mann State, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truckloader from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for the management of the helicopter, the White House Military Administration ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the ground.
“I just wanted you to make sure you’re aware because it’s an unusually widely-lit event in the press,” HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his boss, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the mero.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Pole at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in the event scheduled for 3 a.m., and would remain there before the lawn would be released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on working hours.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by TIME magazine, it remained unclear whether a second crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has clarified whether the event does not contravene this regulation.
“Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told it was not,” the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to care," replied the deputy chief.
The event "Made in America" was declared by the White House as an official event, and Hatch's law did not apply to it.
But even the official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to promote health reform, which was then under development in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
The presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking them only in the interests of photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February when the presidential plane was in the background during his first pre-election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was loaded with complaints about the use of his predecessor’s presidential plane.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House Deputy White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington Aglomeration and on the South Loop to train the President of the United States’ transportation to the White House with accuracy to the inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training positions at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight, carried out for the event "Made in America", was counted to the crew in the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew an additional 11 hours on that day as part of the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not incur any expenses for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter in the South Luzhayak.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Ministry of Defense’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Defense Ministry’s compensation rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit records that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airbase at the air base of the Quantiko Marines in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“To calculate the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These exemplary rates include personal composition, maintenance, and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the REND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of the personal composition, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of the use of a helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things that have been done in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we’re all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
Therefore, it is absolutely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump had interacted with the helicopter, looking at the South Pole during the event, but he was definitely sitting at the driver’s seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky’s representatives, joking with the press about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the president. "I have three of them."
